Comments.
These small black adults have been taken mainly by tree fogging and malaise trapping. They have fine, widely spaced head punctures and slender rosta (
Fig. 27, 28
). The aedeagus (
Fig. 71
) has a short tapered median lobe with the “nozzle-like” pedon apex distinctly constricted and truncate. The tectum is spearhead-shaped. The tegminal cap piece is narrowly finger-like and the knob-like pigmented apex bears a cluster of short setae. Endophallic bands are short and weakly defined.
